    {
      "content": "Overview",
      "pos": [
        594,
        602
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft Azure is an open cloud platform that runs both Microsoft as well as non-Microsoft software which  includes operating systems, application servers, messaging middleware as well as SQL and NoSQL databases from both commercial and open source models.",
      "pos": [
        603,
        860
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Building resilient services on public clouds including Azure requires careful planning and deliberate architecture for both applications servers as well storage layers.",
      "pos": [
        861,
        1029
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra’s distributed storage architecture naturally helps in building highly available systems that are fault tolerant for cluster failures.",
      "pos": [
        1030,
        1173
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra is a cloud scale NoSQL database maintained by Apache Software Foundation at cassandra.apache.org; Cassandra is written in Java and hence runs on both on Windows as well as Linux platforms.",
      "pos": [
        1174,
        1372
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The focus of this article is to show Cassandra deployment on Ubuntu as a single and multi-data center cluster leveraging Microsoft Azure Virtual Machines and Virtual Networks.",
      "pos": [
        1375,
        1550
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The cluster deployment for production optimized workloads is out of scope of this article as it requires multi-disk node configuration, appropriate ring topology design and data modeling to support the needed replication, data consistency, throughput and high availability requirements.",
      "pos": [
        1551,
        1837
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This article takes a fundamental approach to show what is involved in building the Cassandra cluster compared Docker, Chef or Puppet which can make the infrastructure deployment a lot easier.",
      "pos": [
        1840,
        2031
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Deployment Models",
      "pos": [
        2038,
        2059
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft Azure networking allows the deployment of isolated private clusters, the access of which can be restricted to attain fine grained network security.",
      "pos": [
        2061,
        2218
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since this article is about showing the Cassandra deployment at a fundamental level, we will not focus on the consistency level and the optimal storage design for throughput.",
      "pos": [
        2220,
        2394
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here is the list of networking requirements for our hypothetical cluster:",
      "pos": [
        2395,
        2468
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "External systems can’t access Cassandra database from within or outside Azure",
      "pos": [
        2472,
        2549
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra cluster has to be behind a load balancer for thrift traffic",
      "pos": [
        2552,
        2621
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploy Cassandra nodes in two groups in each data center for an enhanced cluster availability",
      "pos": [
        2624,
        2717
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Lock down the cluster so that only application server farm has access to the database directly",
      "pos": [
        2721,
        2815
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "No public networking endpoints other than SSH",
      "pos": [
        2818,
        2863
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each Cassandra node needs a fixed internal IP address",
      "pos": [
        2866,
        2919
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra can be deployed to a single Azure region or to multiple regions based on the distributed nature of the workload.",
      "pos": [
        2921,
        3043
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-region deployment model can be leveraged to serve end users closer to a particular geography through the same Cassandra infrastructure.",
      "pos": [
        3044,
        3185
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra’s built-in node replication takes care of the synchronization of multi-master writes originating from multiple data centers and presents a consistent view of the data to applications.",
      "pos": [
        3186,
        3379
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-region deployment can also help with the risk mitigation of the broader Azure service outages.",
      "pos": [
        3380,
        3480
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra’s tunable consistency and replication topology will help in meeting diverse RPO needs of applications.",
      "pos": [
        3481,
        3593
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single Region Deployment",
      "pos": [
        3601,
        3625
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We will start with a single region deployment and harvest the learnings in creating a multi-region model.",
      "pos": [
        3626,
        3731
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure virtual networking will be used to create isolated subnets so that the network security requirements mentioned above can be met.",
      "pos": [
        3732,
        3866
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The process described in creating the single region deployment uses Ubuntu 14.04 LTS and Cassandra 2.08; however, the process can easily be adopted to the other Linux variants.",
      "pos": [
        3868,
        4044
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following are some of the systemic characteristics of the single region deployment.",
      "pos": [
        4045,
        4132
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>High Availability:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> The Cassandra nodes shown in the Figure 1 are deployed to two availability sets so that the nodes are spread between multiple fault domains for high availability.",
      "pos": [
        4136,
        4321
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VMs annotated with each availability set is mapped to 2 fault domains.",
      "pos": [
        4322,
        4392
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft Azure uses the concept of fault domain to manage unplanned down time (e.g. hardware or software failures) while the concept of upgrade domain (e.g. host or guest OS patching/upgrades, application upgrades) is used for managing scheduled down time.",
      "pos": [
        4394,
        4651
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Please see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Disaster Recovery and High Availability for Azure Applications<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/dn251004.aspx)</ept> for the role of fault and upgrade domains in attaining high availability.",
      "pos": [
        4652,
        4850
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Single region deployment",
      "pos": [
        4855,
        4879
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Figure 1: Single region deployment",
      "pos": [
        4960,
        4994
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that at the time of this writing, Azure doesn’t allow the explicit mapping of a group of VMs to a specific fault domain; consequently, even with the deployment model shown in Figure 1, it is statistically probable that all the virtual machines may be mapped to two fault domains instead of four.",
      "pos": [
        4996,
        5296
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Load Balancing Thrift Traffic:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Thrift client libraries inside the web server connect to the cluster through an internal load balancer.",
      "pos": [
        5299,
        5437
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This requires the process of adding the internal load balancer to the “data” subnet (refer Figure 1) in the context of the cloud service hosting the Cassandra cluster.",
      "pos": [
        5438,
        5605
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once the internal load balancer is defined, each node requires the load balanced endpoint to be added with the annotations of a load balanced set with previously defined load balancer name.",
      "pos": [
        5606,
        5795
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Internal Load Balancing <ept id=\"p1\">](../load-balancer/load-balancer-internal-overview.md)</ept>for more details.",
      "pos": [
        5796,
        5902
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Cluster Seeds:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> It is important to select the most highly available nodes for seeds as the new nodes will communicate with seed nodes to discover the topology of the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        5904,
        6081
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One node from each availability set is designated as seed nodes to avoid single point of failure.",
      "pos": [
        6082,
        6179
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Replication Factor and Consistency Level:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Cassandra’s build-in high-availability and data durability is characterized by the Replication Factor (RF - number of copies of each row stored on the cluster) and Consistency Level (number of replicas to be read/written before returning the result to the caller).",
      "pos": [
        6182,
        6492
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Replication factor is specified during the KEYSPACE (similar to a relational database) creation whereas the consistency level is specified while issuing the CRUD query.",
      "pos": [
        6493,
        6661
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See Cassandra documentation at <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configuring for Consistency<ept id=\"p1\">](http://www.datastax.com/documentation/cassandra/2.0/cassandra/dml/dml_config_consistency_c.html)</ept> for consistency details and the formula for quorum computation.",
      "pos": [
        6662,
        6883
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra supports two types of data integrity models – Consistency and Eventual Consistency; the Replication Factor and Consistency Level will together determine if the data will be consistent as soon as a write operation is complete or it will be eventually consistent.",
      "pos": [
        6885,
        7156
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, specifying QUORUM as the Consistency Level will always ensures data Consistency while any consistency level, below the number of replicas to be written as needed to attain QUORUM (e.g. ONE) results in data being eventually consistent.",
      "pos": [
        7157,
        7404
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The 8-node cluster shown above, with a replication factor of 3 and QUORUM (2 nodes are read or written for consistency) read/write consistency level, can survive the theoretical loss of at the most 1 node per replication group before the application start noticing the failure.",
      "pos": [
        7407,
        7684
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This assumes that all the key spaces have well balanced read/write requests.",
      "pos": [
        7685,
        7761
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following are the parameters we will use for the deployed cluster:",
      "pos": [
        7763,
        7833
      ]
