    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Azure Considerations for Cassandra Cluster:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Microsoft Azure Virtual Machines capability uses Azure Blob storage for disk persistence; Azure Storage saves 3 replicas of each disk for high durability.",
      "pos": [
        9373,
        9575
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That means each row of data inserted into a Cassandra table is already stored in 3 replicas and hence data consistency is already taken care of even if the Replication Factor (RF) is 1.",
      "pos": [
        9576,
        9761
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The main problem with Replication Factor being 1 is that the application will experience downtime even if a single Cassandra node fails.",
      "pos": [
        9762,
        9898
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, if a node is down for the problems (e.g. hardware, system software failures) recognized by Azure Fabric Controller, it will provision a new node in its place using the same storage drives.",
      "pos": [
        9899,
        10096
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Provisioning a new node to replace the old one may take a few minutes.",
      "pos": [
        10097,
        10167
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Similarly for planned maintenance activities like guest OS changes, Cassandra upgrades and application changes Azure Fabric Controller performs rolling upgrades of the nodes in the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        10169,
        10358
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Rolling upgrades also may take down a few nodes at a time and hence the cluster may experience brief downtime for a few partitions.",
      "pos": [
        10360,
        10491
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, the data will not be lost due to the built-in Azure Storage redundancy.",
      "pos": [
        10492,
        10572
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For systems deployed to Azure that doesn’t require high availability (e.g. around 99.9 which is equivalent to 8.76 hrs/year; see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>High Availability<ept id=\"p1\">](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High_availability)</ept> for details) you may be able to run with RF=1 and Consistency Level=ONE.",
      "pos": [
        10576,
        10845
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For applications with high availability requirements, RF=3 and Consistency Level=QUORUM will tolerate the down time of one of the nodes one of the replicas.",
      "pos": [
        10847,
        11003
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "RF=1 in traditional deployments (e.g. on-premise) can’t be used due to the possible data loss resulting from problems like disk failures.",
      "pos": [
        11004,
        11141
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-region Deployment",
      "pos": [
        11149,
        11172
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra’s data center aware replication and consistency model described above helps with the multi-region deployment out of the box without the need for any external tooling.",
      "pos": [
        11173,
        11349
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is quite different from the traditional relational databases where the setup for database mirroring for multi-master writes can be quite complex.",
      "pos": [
        11350,
        11500
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cassandra in a multi-region set up can help with the usage scenarios including the following:",
      "pos": [
        11501,
        11594
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Proximity based deployment:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Multi-tenant applications, with clear mapping of tenant users -to-region, can be benefited by the multi-region cluster’s low latencies.",
      "pos": [
        11597,
        11764
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example a learning management systems for educational institutions can deploy a distributed cluster in East US and West US regions to serve the respective campuses for transactional as well as analytics.",
      "pos": [
        11765,
        11972
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The data can be locally consistent at the time reads and writes and can be eventually consistent across both the regions.",
      "pos": [
        11973,
        12094
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are other examples like media distribution, e-commerce and anything and everything that serves geo concentrated user base is a good use case for this deployment model.",
      "pos": [
        12095,
        12268
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>High Availability:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Redundancy is a key factor in attaining high availability of software and hardware; see Building Reliable Cloud Systems on Microsoft Azure for details.",
      "pos": [
        12271,
        12445
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On Microsoft Azure, the only reliable way of achieving true redundancy is by deploying a multi-region cluster.",
      "pos": [
        12446,
        12556
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Applications can be deployed in an active-active or active-passive mode and if one of the regions is down, Azure Traffic Manager can redirect traffic to the active region.",
      "pos": [
        12557,
        12728
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With the single region deployment, if the availability is 99.9, a two-region deployment can attain an availability of 99.9999 computed by the formula: (1-(1-0.999) * (1-0.999))*100); see the above paper for details.",
      "pos": [
        12730,
        12945
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Disaster Recovery:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Multi-region Cassandra cluster, if properly designed, can withstand catastrophic data center outages.",
      "pos": [
        12948,
        13072
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If one region is down, the application deployed to other regions can start serving the end users.",
      "pos": [
        13073,
        13170
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Like any other business continuity implementations, the application has to be tolerant for some data loss resulting from the data in the asynchronous pipeline.",
      "pos": [
        13171,
        13330
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, Cassandra makes the recovery much swifter than the time taken by traditional database recovery processes.",
      "pos": [
        13331,
        13445
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Figure 2 shows the typical multi-region deployment model with eight nodes in each region.",
      "pos": [
        13446,
        13535
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Both regions are mirror images of each other for the same of symmetry; real world designs depend on the workload type (e.g. transactional or analytical), RPO, RTO, data consistency and availability requirements.",
      "pos": [
        13536,
        13747
      ]
    },
